 [Thursdoids*], informing the community on what is what.\n[/list]\n\n[b]To sum it up:[/b]\n\nPZ is the realization of a unique approach to the zombie genre and an outstanding game in its own rights. Even after hundreds of hours you might find a hidden little feature or something you wouldnt expect in a game that is developed by only a handful people (like: Your character waking up in the middle of the night because he/she had a bad dream). While the Singeplayer is neat, the game is best be played in multiplayer, since there are still key features of the game missing (NPCs) this is possibly the best approach to not die of lonelyness in the world of PZ. \n\n\n[h1] What I dont like about PZ: [/h1]\n\n[list]\n[*] If you look up \"development hell\" in a lexicon, you will most likely find a reference to PZ somewhere in between.\n[*] Promised key features (Non player characters, Animations) are still not implemented in the game.\n[*] There are three separate builds of the game that you can play now, each one holding different features, being at a different stage of development. A general test branch, the stable branch and a vehicle test branch.\n[*] The player base is very, very small. It is at best a few hundred players, meaning its relatively hard to find a good server when you dont play with friends in the first place.\n[*] Guns (in the vanilla game) are pretty useless and only bring hundreds of zombies to your base, which will ultimately force you to abandon it.\n[*] Some of the aforementioned professions are outright useless (Electrician, Cook, and a few others) since they either provide no meaningful unique talents or fall short compared to other professions.\n[*] Devs dont keep their own timelines, because they decide to have none at all. I would argue that this games development pace is only second to that of the DayZ Standalone. (This point has been debated on the forums to some extend recently, so take this with a grain of salt)\n[*] Internal work orders and priorities are clearly in disarray at TIS. Polishing the game is not one of their top priorities.\n[*] Most of the mentioned weekly reports are pretty much fluff only and provide rarely any substantial information about key features.\n[/list]\n\n[b]To sum it up:[/b]\n\nPersonally, at the moment i can not give this game a recommendation since the abysmal development time is outright unacceptable. NPCs, while they were already in the game (in a rudimentary fashion) have been in development for several years now and for the past 2 or 3 years no one has heard a word on them. While the devs said that eventually, after implementing a new animation system, they would talk about them that has yet to happen. Animations itself have been delayed by almost two years now, after the devs generated quite a bit of hype in early 2016 with a showcase of the new animation system, making it sound as if great things were about to happen. Well, nothing happened and ever since they have pretty much gone dark about it. Every now and then a single line is dropped in their weekly reports but 80% of these reports is them telling us that they will add a formula for gas consumption for cars or a rephrase for \"we are working on something.\" If you are one of those that are waiting for information on animations (you >might< get lucky) or NPCs (you wont hear a word) - try not to get your hopes up.\n\nSome have even called this game \"Abandonware\" on the forums - which is a lie, since development still happens.  Still, personally I think that they waste their resources on gimmicks and marginal features that find their way in one of the several test branches, while already existing core elements (like professions, aiming system, etc, etc) are still far from polished. One of the most recent examples is their latest report (28.09.2017) in which they showcase their progress on the cars. Cars like ambulances now have flashing lights and even some button to change the pattern of the lights - amazing. What cars still do not have, is a functioning inventory. Full loads of items still disappear when players leave the area - [url=https://theindiestone.com/forums/index.php?/topic/22436-released-vehicle-tech-test-build/&do=findComment&comment=257573]a bug that I personally reported several times around four months ago on the forums[/url]. Losing full inventory loads does not seem to be much of an issue for the devs at TIS, at least not when compared to implementing a blue flashy light. If you are trying to play this game in Multiplayer, then be aware that these issues still persist and that frustration and inventory losses are still a common thing. In a lenghty discussion on the forums I was told that if you have a lacking background in game design, these decisions might be hard to grasp. I agree to some extend but nobody can tell me with a straight face that a game like this has to be in development for more than 6 years,while some of the most prominent features are still missing. In that regard I would like to warn any potential buyer that should you decide to buy this game, then do it only if you are okay with what you will currently get and dont buy it if you are hoping for NPCs or such a thing. You will get disappointed like I have.\n\nI hyped a group of friends to play this game under the impression that animations were soon to be dropped (early 2016) and out of my friends I am the only one who still plays this game at times. The others got bored or angry pretty fast and dropped this game like a hot potato. \n\n[b]TL;DR[/b]\n\nGame could be awesome, but its development is an outright mess.\nBuy it only if you are ok with what the game currently is and dont get your hopes up that it will be done anytime soon.\n\n\nEdit #1 (21.09.2017): Mondoids became \"Thursdoids\". Devs just changed their name and shifted the reports from Mondays to Thursdays.'\n\nEdit #2 (28.09.2017): Added the part about flashing lights on cars vs. losing full trunk loads of items."}, {"votes_dow