learning to \"move things around\" from your bags to containers and such, getting your feet under you, then...all your \"The Walking Dead\" and \"Dawn of the Dead\" training starts coming out.\n\nOnce you've worked the interface out and are comfortable with it enough to function, you then slip easily into your \"survival boots\". Your senses go high, you mind starts running in the background on its own, plotting out what-ifs for anything that might happen, all the while you are actively looting your first house (likely your own house). \n\nAs you gather things you quickly come to understand that you can't (and shouldn't) take everything. You are now alone in the dark. You have no help coming...and as long as you stay quiet and inconspicuous, you have a lot of time to think on your plan of survival and start to pool resources together and get your feet under you.\n\nThe crafting engine can seem overwhelming at first, but it is actually quite forgiving as long as you have the curiosity to read the possible designs and think to yourself \"how can I make this help me\". And to have a hoarding nature will help...gather ALL the stuff you find and put it into a workshop style environment. Then you sit down and quietly tinker all night long from one thing to another. \n\nThe physiological and psychological aspects to the game are amazing, even to this old survival sim veteran. As I sat there with a screwdriver, disassembling a remote control for its I.R. sensor, I looked over and realized that I have become well-adapted to being (in this case) 5 things at once...I am a little hungry...I am a bit tired...I am getting bored...I am having some pain in my left forearm (due to glass from breaking a window last night)...and I am being soothed by the sound of the rain outside. The depth of ailments, conditions, and afflictions are really amazing. If you were to be stabbed, you wouldn't just \"Lose 25 hp and get 'bleeding' condition\". No no...you would take the hit...stab...I've been hurt...then blood spurt 3 seconds later...I am bleeding and it's severe...then 10 seconds after, I am getting scared (seeing so much of your own blood) and in some pain...then 20 seconds after as you stuble towards your camp, I am in tremendous pain and am wailing out and cannot help it...30 seconds...I am cold and trembling and sliding into shock. \nApply sterile bandages (you made yesterday from whiskey and ripped bed sheets)...and the conditions slowly subside over time. This makes for an IMMENSELY more engrossing event than \"I got stabbed and lost 25 hp\". \n\nI am just scratching the surface of the jewel...and already I have declared \"You have SOO earned my money on this game\". I bought my own copy and am likely to purchase a 4-pack for the rest of my gaming unit. Multiplayer HAS to be just righteous. \n\nSo for TLDR: Well worth the money, take 10 mins and learn the interface, then go live your life in this REALISTIC survival simulation. Make your own server, tweak your \"in my end of the world zombie apocalypse things would be like this...\" settings. Then immerse yourself into a sim that will carry you for 100s of hours as you push your boundries and your imagination."}]}